

## 1Ô∏è‚É£ / ‚Äì Root Directory

Purpose:

 Top-level of the filesystem tree.
 All other directories branch from /.
 Houses essential directories like /bin, /etc, /home, /var, /usr.

Key Points:

 Do not store personal files directly here ‚Äì they should go under /home or /srv.
 Critical for booting ‚Äì deleting files here may break the system.

Commands:


ls -l /
tree -L 1 /    # shows only top-level directories


---

## 2Ô∏è‚É£ /bin ‚Äì Essential User Binaries

Purpose:

 Contains basic command-line utilities for all users.
 Commands required for both single-user mode and multi-user mode.

Examples of commands:

 ls, cat, cp, mv, , date

Key Points:

 Should never contain local or third-party software.
 Used during system repair if /usr is unavailable.

Command:


ls /bin
which 


---

## 3Ô∏è‚É£ /sbin ‚Äì System Binaries (Root/Admin)

Purpose:

 Contains system administration commands primarily for root.
 Used for system repair, maintenance, booting.

Examples:

 fdisk ‚Üí partition management
 ifconfig ‚Üí configure network interfaces
 mount ‚Üí mount filesystems

Command:


ls /sbin


---

## 4Ô∏è‚É£ /usr ‚Äì User Programs

Purpose:

 Stores non-essential binaries, libraries, and documentation.
 Mounted read-only on multi-user systems (can be shared over network).

Subdirectories:

 /usr/bin ‚Üí user programs
 /usr/sbin ‚Üí administrative programs
 /usr/lib ‚Üí libraries
 /usr/share ‚Üí documentation, man pages, icons, etc.

Commands:

ls /usr/bin | head
ls /usr/share/doc


Key Insight:

 /usr is usually the largest directory because it contains most installed software.

---

## 5Ô∏è‚É£ /etc ‚Äì Configuration Files

Purpose:

 Holds system-wide configuration files.
 Only static text files; binaries are not stored here.

Examples:

 /etc/passwd ‚Üí user accounts
 /etc/fstab ‚Üí filesystem mount info
 /etc/hosts ‚Üí IP to hostname mapping
 /etc/ssh/sshd_config ‚Üí SSH server config

Command:


ls /etc
cat /etc/fstab


Best Practice:

 Don‚Äôt store scripts or binaries here. Only configs.

---

## 6Ô∏è‚É£ /var ‚Äì Variable Data

Purpose:

 Stores files that change frequently during system operation.
 Includes logs, caches, spool files.

Important Subdirectories:

 /var/log ‚Üí system and service logs
 /var/tmp ‚Üí temporary files (persist across reboot)
 /var/spool ‚Üí print queues, mail queues
 /var/lib ‚Üí state information for applications (e.g., databases)

Commands:


ls /var/log
tail -f /var/log/messages


Key Insight:

 /var is dynamic; monitor disk usage here, especially /var/log.

---

## 7Ô∏è‚É£ /home ‚Äì User Home Directories

Purpose:

 Each regular user gets a personal directory here.
 Stores personal files, settings, and hidden configuration files (dotfiles).

Example: /home/rohit contains .rc, .ssh, and personal documents.

Commands:


ls -la /home/rohit
du -sh /home/


---

## 8Ô∏è‚É£ /root ‚Äì Root User Home

Purpose:

 Home directory for the root user.
 Similar to /home, but only for administrative tasks.

Command:


ls -la /root


---

## 9Ô∏è‚É£ /tmp ‚Äì Temporary Files

Purpose:

 Temporary files created by users and applications.
 Usually cleared on reboot (depends on distro).

Command:


ls /tmp
rm -rf /tmp/mytempfile


Key Points:

 Do not store critical data here.
 Applications often write temporary session files here.

---

## üîü /dev ‚Äì Device Files

Purpose:

 Special files representing hardware devices or pseudo-devices.

Examples:

 /dev/sda ‚Üí first hard disk
 /dev/tty ‚Üí terminal
 /dev/null ‚Üí discard output

Commands:


ls -l /dev
ls -l /dev/sda


Key Insight:

 Linux treats everything as a file, including hardware devices.

---

## 1Ô∏è‚É£1Ô∏è‚É£ /proc ‚Äì Process & Kernel Info (Virtual Filesystem)

Purpose:

 Virtual filesystem representing kernel and process information.
 Files aren‚Äôt stored on disk; they‚Äôre generated on access.

Examples:

 /proc/cpuinfo ‚Üí CPU info
 /proc/meminfo ‚Üí memory info
 /proc/<PID> ‚Üí process info

Commands:


cat /proc/cpuinfo
cat /proc/meminfo
ls /proc/$$      # current shell


---

## 1Ô∏è‚É£2Ô∏è‚É£ /sys ‚Äì Kernel & Device Info (Virtual FS)

Purpose:

 Provides sysfs ‚Äì kernel interface for devices and drivers.
 Used by udev and system scripts.

Commands:


ls /sys/class/net   # list network interfaces


---

## 1Ô∏è‚É£3Ô∏è‚É£ /opt ‚Äì Optional/Third-Party Software

Purpose:

 For manually installed or third-party applications.
 Example: Google Chrome, VMware, custom software.

Command:


ls /opt


---

## 1Ô∏è‚É£4Ô∏è‚É£ /lib ‚Äì Essential Libraries

Purpose:

 Shared libraries needed by binaries in /bin and /sbin.
 On 64-bit systems, /lib64 exists for 64-bit libraries.

Command:


ls /lib
ls /lib64


---

## 1Ô∏è‚É£5Ô∏è‚É£ /media & /mnt ‚Äì Mount Points

Purpose:

 /media ‚Üí automatic mount points for removable media (USB, CD-ROM)
 /mnt ‚Üí temporary manual mount points

Command:


mount | grep /media
mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt


---

## 1Ô∏è‚É£6Ô∏è‚É£ /srv ‚Äì Service Data

Purpose:

 Contains data for system services.
 Example: /srv/www ‚Üí web server data, /srv/ftp ‚Üí FTP server files.

Command:


ls /srv


---

## 1Ô∏è‚É£7Ô∏è‚É£ Hidden Files (dotfiles)

 Files starting with . are hidden, often configuration files in a user‚Äôs home.
 Example: .rc, .vimrc, .ssh/

Command:


ls -la /home/rohit


---

## üîπ Summary Table of Major Directories

| Directory    | Purpose                      | Example Files/Commands |
| ------------ | ---------------------------- | ---------------------- |
| /          | Root                         | ls /                   |
| /bin       | Essential user binaries      | ls, cp, mv             |
| /sbin      | Admin binaries               | fdisk, ifconfig        |
| /usr       | Installed software           | /usr/bin, /usr/lib     |
| /etc       | Configuration files          | /etc/fstab, /etc/hosts |
| /var       | Variable files               | /var/log, /var/spool   |
| /home      | User home                    | /home/username         |
| /root      | Root home                    | /root/.rc          |
| /tmp       | Temporary files              | /tmp/testfile          |
| /dev       | Device files                 | /dev/sda, /dev/null    |
| /proc      | Process/kernel info          | /proc/cpuinfo          |
| /sys       | Kernel & device info         | /sys/class/net         |
| /opt       | Optional software            | /opt/google/chrome     |
| /lib       | Libraries                    | /lib, /lib64           |
| /media     | Auto-mounted removable media | /media/usb             |
| /mnt       | Temporary mounts             | mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt   |
| /srv       | Service data                 | /srv/www               |
| Hidden files | User configs                 | .rc, .ssh          |


